segments.text: The Saturday class stage, but there was a time I understand they had Saturday classes.
And you didn't have a surplus of cash.
Right.
And you had maybe Saturday night and Sunday off.
And so, you know, where do you go, you know?
Occasionally, this was like my second year, my brother was at the University of Texas.
He had been in the high school in the Marine Corps and he was a couple years older than I am.
And then he went back to college and so he had kind of about caught up with me I guess.
He was at the University of Texas and I used to go over and visit him, go to Austin.
Okay, kind of some summary questions.
As you look back on it, those years, what did A&M do well?
Academically or anything else?
Well, I think there were some good faculty members that taught classes and that spent a lot of time with students, or would, and would work with you about things.
I like Harry Korder, who was English.
K-R-O-I-T-O-R. Yeah, Korder.
He's, I think, dead now.
You know, he was, you know, helped me a lot in terms of writing.
You know, in the sense he'd sit down and would work with you on, let's see what's wrong with this sentence type stuff.
I don't know too many people how to do that today.
Who else were there that you would, if you had them all around here now, you would thank?
Well, you for one, and I think Corder, and Brown in sociology.
What did I do?
Well, I think just mentored, you know, a time like we knew you were going to be a veterinarian and is this the right choice?
And, you know, you gave me a lot of encouragement about, in fact, I think when I took the Old South course, I wasn't yet, I was still in vet medicine.
I took it as an elective, one of the electives that you could do, and it's just out of interest to Southern history, you know.
And encouragement in the sense of papers that you'd written and other things like that.
Political science, anybody?
No, not really.
I can say political science came kind of more at Midwestern, influence of various and sundry people.
They had some really good young faculty members at Midwestern.
You had, of course, Isabelle Hunt, who was something of a legend.
But there was a guy, Hoffman, University of Chicago PhD, taught political theory.
You had a guy, Moon, Korean, ended up at Arlington, who taught comparative government.
Jim Wright, who was from Duke.
Duke, yeah, Jim taught political theory.
You had a guy, Hoffman, who taught American politics, Congress, and the presidency.
And these were, you know, from 20 degrees, and these were good people.
And very, you know, small classes, lots of class discussion, you know, lots of time on court cases, you know, constitutional law and civil liberties.
So I think that was it.
The history faculty, there were some interesting people there, but I think it retracted more to the people that were in political science as opposed to history.

looking at it as objectively as possible what creates aggie spirit yeah i know i keep hearing this about the aggie family and aggie spirit and and you know i think it's not any one thing there's from the email i received you would think it was bonfire uh you know the you know but but really i think it may begin with fish camp

which used to be a lot different deal than it is now it was a drawn out thing and i think they used to take them out to junction and stuff like that there's that there's there's the silver taps there's the the aggie lore the you know the the bullshit stories most of which probably aren't true
Like you follow these people that give the campus tours, the guys that walk backwards.
You ought to do that one time and listen to what, have you done that?
You need to do it.
They go by the academic building all the time.
You can just probably, maybe go over and ask for a campus tour when you could do one and don't tell them who you are and you'll find out some interesting things.
The tree in front of Bolton Hall was planted by the first class of Aggies at Texas A&M.
Did you know that?
Not in 1913, as the photographs show.
Do you know why they stopped polishing the dome on the academic building?
Because it was blinding the pilots and they landed at Easterwood Airport.
I mean, there's just these amazing things.
I mean, they're just ludicrous.
All of the logs at Bonfire are cut with axes.
I mean, it just goes on and on.
So there's all this mythology.
It's almost like the Texas mythology.
You can make a point that the people at the Alamo were idiots.
Not heroes, but idiots.
There wasn't any way they were going to beat Napoleon's army.
with the damn Kentucky long rifles and a couple of cannons.
But there's this myth, and there's a lot of that at A&M.
And all of that, I think, adds to it.
And lightly, the idea that you're an Aggie because you're special in the sense that you can get into A&M.
And that makes you special.
Not everybody can get accepted.
That wasn't true back then, I think.
They gave you the Aggie, you know, which hands are yours.
Are there some other events that you haven't mentioned that you think add to that spirit?
Well, the band, the music, the songs, the yells, the core trips, all of those things at least at that point added to the kind of Aggie camaraderie.
And of course there was a lot of, everybody's out in the hall sitting up against the wall with their knees drawn up and the company commanders marching up and down the hall.
And you're talking about what good Aggies do and what bad Aggies, you know, do and so on, that kind of stuff, you know.
Why did you come to A&M?
We got a fight in Texas Aggie.
You didn't get ready to get an education.
That's the other education.
And you know, Haskell, judging by the email messages that I got on Bonfire, these people got the other education because they can't spell, they can't write, and they can't think.
All right, what did you do?
What special things did you get out of being here two years?
What did it mean to you to have been here two years?
I don't know whether anything particularly special.
Well, it must have been something because you didn't turn down a job opportunity.
You could have gone somewhere else.
Right, but I think that was more a matter of a number of things, why you accepted the job.
And it was, you know, pay.
It was resources that they were willing to give you.
It was Gibbons, who was a very dynamic sort of individual, you know.
the colleagues that you were going to be with, that group of four that recruited you, those kinds of things that overcome the sort of negative feelings that you had.
There was also a lot of repression of any sort of thought out of the ordinary.
I still remember where
You know, there was a case of somebody who didn't get into who's who, and of course somebody overrode the committee's decision.
And the battalion wrote an essay entitled, you know, 49 Who's Who and One Who's He, and all hell broke loose.
You know, the battalion editor got fired back when they could do those kinds of things over.
Basically telling the truth that some dean exercised political influence to get this guy.
He was somebody who was in the corps, on corps staff, but he was really kind of a guy that was disliked by a lot of people, which is why he didn't get who's who.
Let's see.
Two other questions then.
Let's make believe somebody walks up to you and gives you a million-dollar check that has only one specific requirement.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you can decide the use that A&M would make for that money.
If you could make a big, meaningful gift, what would it be for?
Undergraduate scholarship.
for what
How would the, who, what undergraduates?
Well, I might pick political science instead of liberal arts.
How would you select the specific ones?
I don't know that I would want to do that.
No, but you'd have the university select them on the basis of what?
On the basis of merit and need.
Merit and need.
Okay.
All right.
Then the last question is a serious one.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M?
I think, you know, about it.

There are aspects of it that, you know, you say it really could be a great university, but it really could meet the 2020 vision, but I don't think it's going to, unless somebody begins to take that bonfire report seriously.
I think that was very devastating to, or it should be viewed as being very devastating
the people in charge of this place.

But I haven't heard anybody say or haven't heard anyone ask, and maybe they will, you know, what can we do to address that problem among the students at Texas A&M University and among the administration?
It's not just confined to the students.
I have a lot of it in the administration.
And some of that's because over the years you keep hiring, you know, your graduates to come back, you know, bachelor, master, Ph.D., you know, retired.
I mean, look at engineering, the degree to which that's true, agriculture, the degree to which that's true.
And, you know, that ought to be something that somebody really ought to be concerned with.
And maybe, you know, I admit Bowen's been very tied up with
We're just getting, you know, to this point.
And obviously he must have made the right decision.
He made both sides mad.
And I respect, I think what he did was the right thing.
I might have gone another year without Bonfire.
But at some point maybe he will address that issue.
We, Faculty Senate Executive Committee asked to meet with him at some point and we want to talk about that aspect of it.
And how do you address the change of culture?
I don't know.
What's going on?
